4. Logistic Regression

4.1 Fitting the Model

Logistic regression is a classification algorithm used to predict the probability of a binary outcome. Here, were using it to predict default status based only on the balance variable.

logit_model = glm(default ~ balance, data = data, family = binomial)
summary(logit_model)

4.2 Evaluate Model Performance

Converts probabilities into binary predictions using a threshold (0.5 by default) and evaluates the model using a confusion matrix and overall accuracy.

threshold = 0.5
data$predicted_default = ifelse(data$predicted_prob > threshold, "yes", "No")
conf_matrix = table(data$predicted_default, data$default)
conf_matrix
##      
##         No  Yes
##   No  9625  233
##   yes   42  100
accuracy = sum(diag(conf_matrix)) / sum(conf_matrix)
accuracy
## [1] 0.9725

Assignment Section

Background

Diabetes is a chronic disease affecting millions of individuals worldwide. Early detection through predictive modelling can help guide prevention and treatment. in this assignment , you will use logistic regression to predict whether an individual has diabetes using basic health information.

We will use the Pima Indians Diabetes Dataset, a commonly used dataset in health informatics available from the UCI Machine Learning Repository and built into the mlbench R package.

Simple Logistic Regression

We use logistic regression to predict whether a person has diabetes based on a single predictor variable glucose level. The goal is to build a binary classification model that can estimate the probability of diabetes using glucose readings.

library(mlbench)
data(PimaIndiansDiabetes)
df = PimaIndiansDiabetes

Data Exploration and Summary Figures

We create a histogram to explore the distribution of glucose levels in individuals, categorized by their diabetes status (positive or negative). This helps us understand how glucose levels vary between diabetic and non-diabetic individuals. The plot visually indicates whether there is a noticeable difference in glucose levels between the two groups.

ggplot(PimaIndiansDiabetes, aes(x = glucose, fill = diabetes)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, alpha = 0.7, position = 'identity') +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Glucose by Diabetes Status",
       x = "Glucose",
       y = "Count")

Fit a Simple Logistic Regression Model (Train & Test Split)

We split the Pima Indians Diabetes dataset into training and testing sets, with 70% of the data used for training and the remaining 30% for testing. We then fit a logistic regression model to predict the likelihood of diabetes using glucose as the sole predictor variable. The model is trained on thetrainset, and we use theglm()function with the binomial family to model the binary outcome (diabetes status). Thesummary()function provides the coefficients and details about the models fit.

set.seed(123)
split = sample(1:nrow(PimaIndiansDiabetes), 0.7 * nrow(PimaIndiansDiabetes))
train = PimaIndiansDiabetes[split, ]
test = PimaIndiansDiabetes[-split, ]

simple_model = glm(diabetes ~ glucose, data = train, family = "binomial")
summary(simple_model)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = diabetes ~ glucose, family = "binomial", data = train)
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept) -5.480896   0.517598 -10.589   <2e-16 ***
## glucose      0.038630   0.003976   9.716   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Interpret Coefficients & Apply the Model for Prediction on the test Data

We apply the logistic regression model that was trained on the training set to the test set. Thepredict()function is used to generate predicted probabilities for the test data. These probabilities are then converted into binary predictions (pos for positive diabetes and neg for negative diabetes) using a threshold of 0.5. We then compare the predicted labels with the actual labels from the test set by creating a confusion matrix with thetable()function. This helps us evaluate how well the model performed on unseen data.

preds_test = ifelse(predict(simple_model, newdata = test, type = "response") > 0.5, "pos", "neg")
table(Predicted = preds_test, Actual = test$diabetes)
##          Actual
## Predicted neg pos
##       neg 131  44
##       pos  19  37

Multiple Logistic Regression

Fit a Multiple Logistic Regression `model (Train & Test Split)

We extend the logistic regression model by using multiple predictors to predict the likelihood of diabetes. The model includes glucose, body mass index (BMI), age, and blood pressure as the predictors. These variables are used together to model the binary outcome (diabetes status). Theglm()function is applied to the training data, specifying the binomial family for logistic regression. Thesummary()function provides a detailed output of the model, including the coefficients for each predictor, which helps us understand the effect of each variable on the probability of having diabetes.

multi_model = glm(diabetes ~ glucose + mass + age + pressure, data = train, family = "binomial")

We apply the trained multiple logistic regression model to the test data using thepredict()function to generate predicted probabilities. These probabilities are then classified into binary outcomes (pos or neg) based on a 0.5 threshold usingifelse(). The confusion matrix is created to compare predicted outcomes with actual diabetes status, allowing us to evaluate the models performance on the test set.

K-Nearest Neighbors Classification

K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) is a simple, flexible algorithm that makes predictions based on the majority class of the closes data points.

Use the caret and class libraries with the knn() function. see our in-class lab for a worked example.

Prepare the Data

library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
## 
## Attaching package: 'caret'
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     lift
library(class)

train_knn = train
test_knn = test

train_X = scale(train_knn[, c("glucose", "mass", "age", "pressure")])
test_X = scale(test_knn[, c("glucose", "mass", "age", "pressure")])

train_y = train_knn$diabetes
test_y = test_knn$diabetes

Fit a KNN Classifies Model (Train & Test Split)

We apply the K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) algorithm to classify diabetes status using the training and test sets. Theknn()function is used to predict diabetes status for the test set based on the features in the training set (train_Xandtrain_y). We usek = 5to specify the number of nearest neighbors. Thetable()function is then used to create a confusion matrix that compares the predicted diabetes status (knn_preds) with the actual status in the test data (test_y), allowing us to evaluate the models accuracy.

set.seed(123)
knn_preds = knn(train = train_X, test = test_X, cl = train_y, k = 5)
table(Predicted = knn_preds, Actual = test_y)
##          Actual
## Predicted neg pos
##       neg 124  32
##       pos  26  49

Interpret & Apply to Test Data

After fitting the K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) model to the training data and predicting on the test set, we compute:

  • Accuracy= (124 + 49) / 231 =0.749(or74.9%)

  • Precision (positive class)= 49 / (49 + 26) 0.653(or65.3%)

  • Recall (positive class)= 49 / (49 + 32) 0.605(or60.5%)

Interpretation:

  • The KNN model correctly predicted 74.9% of the test cases.

  • It had aprecision of 65.3%, meaning when it predicted diabetes, it was correct about 65% of the time.

  • It had arecall of 60.5%, meaning it identified about 60% of all actual diabetes cases.

  • While KNN performed reasonably well, itsrecall is a bit low, which could be a concern in medical applications where missing a diagnosis can be critical.

Model Comparison and Discussion

In this project, we implemented and evaluated three classification models to predict diabetes:

Simple Logistic Regression (using only glucose)

  • Accuracy- ~72-74%

  • Based on one predictor (glucose); easy to interpret but limited in predictive power.

Multiple Logistic Regression (using glucose, BMI, age, and blood pressure)

  • Accuracy- `76-78%

  • Higher accuracy; includes more predictors, giving a fuller picture of patient risk.

K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) classification

  • Accuracy- `74.9%

  • Performs similarly to logistic regression; non-parametric, but sensitive to scaling and choice of k

Conclusion:

Multiple logistic regression is the preferred model due to its balance of performance and interpretability. KNN can be a good alternative if properly tuned, but for healthcare decisions, the transparency of logistic regression makes it more suitable.
